{# ══ Activity 1 — Putting It All Together ════════════════════════════ #}

{% call activitySection(1, "Putting It All Together", "layers") %}
<p>
  This final unit integrates all skills developed across the course. You have now
  studied propositions and truth, argument structure, deductive and inductive reasoning,
  conditional logic, truth tables, fallacies, and argument mapping. In this unit, you
  will apply all of these tools to evaluate extended, real-world arguments.
</p>
<p>
  The core skill of applied logic is not knowing the names of fallacies or argument forms —
  it is being able to read an argument, understand its structure, evaluate the quality of
  its reasoning, and reach a justified verdict on whether its conclusion is well-supported.
</p>
<p>
  Keep the <strong>critical evaluation framework</strong> from Unit 9 close at hand:
</p>
<ol style="color:#ddd; line-height:2.3; font-size:0.92rem;">
  <li>Identify the main conclusion.</li>
  <li>Identify the premises.</li>
  <li>Identify sub-conclusions and hidden assumptions.</li>
  <li>Determine the argument structure (linked / convergent / serial).</li>
  <li>Evaluate the truth of each premise.</li>
  <li>Evaluate the strength of evidence.</li>
  <li>Check for formal and informal fallacies.</li>
  <li>Evaluate validity (deductive) or strength (inductive).</li>
  <li>Evaluate soundness or cogency of the conclusion.</li>
</ol>
{% endcall %}


